<chapter xml:id="chapter-avg-rate" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Average and instantaneous rates</title>

<!-- Average rate of accumulation. Differentials and approximate rate of accumulation. -->

<section xml:id="section-avg-rate-intro">
<title>Averaging variation over an extended time period</title>

<example xml:id="example-avg-rate-rainfall">
	<title>Average rainfall</title>

	<p>
	A rainfall gauge is essentially a graduated cylinder that collects rain as it falls.
	But instead of being marked with volume measurements,
	it is marked with height measurements.
	</p>

	<p>
	With rain in the forecast,
	you decide to set out a rain gauge at 10 o'clock in the evening,
	even though it is not currently raining.
	You check on the rain gauge at 8 o'clock the next morning,
	and find that it has collected an amount of water so that the gauge reads
	<quantity><mag>4</mag><unit base="metre" prefix="milli"></unit></quantity>.
	This measurement means that if the ground was perfectly flat and impermeable so that the rain could neither run off nor be absorbed by the ground,
	you'd be standing in a large puddle
	<quantity><mag>4</mag><unit base="metre" prefix="milli"></unit></quantity>
	deep.
	</p>

	<p>
	So the average rate of accumulation over those 10 hours was
	<quantity><mag>0.4</mag><unit base="metre" prefix="milli" /><per base="hour" /></quantity>.
	</p>

</example>

<p>
The average rate of accumulation measurement in <xref ref="example-avg-rate-rainfall" /> does not provide any information about the intensity of the weather that produced the rain.
Was the accumulation caused by a light drizzle for most of the night,
or by a sudden downpour that only lasted a few minutes at some point?
There is no way to tell because this was not observed.
<em>Average</em> rate of accumulation replaces all the minute-to-minute or second-to-second variation in the actual rate of accumulation with a single, constant rate of accumulation,
similarly to our use of step functions in <xref ref="chapter-step" />.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-avg-rate">
	<title>Average rate of accumulation</title>
	<p> The constant rate of accumulation that produces the same accumulation amount over a given time period. </p>
</definition>

<p>
Calculating average rate of accumulation from a quantity model is simple <mdash />
simply divide the accumulation amount by the time duration.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-avg-rate-speed">
	<title>Average speed</title>

	<p>
	Consider again our Camrose-Wetaskiwin trip from <xref ref="example-step-car-trip" />,
	also discussed in <xref ref="subsection-integ-simplifying-models" />.
	The actual total distance travelled according to the <q>more realistic</q> rate model in <xref ref="figure-integ-camrose-wetaskiwin" /> is approximately
	<quantity><mag>50.5</mag><unit base="metre" prefix="kilo" /></quantity>,
	and the trip lasts a total of
	<quantity><mag>39</mag><unit base="minute" /></quantity>,
	for an average speed of
	<!-- <me> \frac{50.5}{39/60} \approx <quantity><mag>77.7</mag><unit base="metre" prefix="kilo" /><per base="hour" /></quantity> </me>. -->
	<me> \frac{50.5}{39/60} \approx 77.7 </me>
	in kilometres per hour.
	If it were possible to go from parked to full speed instantaneously,
	maintain that full speed constantly over the full
	<quantity><mag>39</mag><unit base="minute" /></quantity>,
	and then go from full speed to parked again instantaneously at the destination,
	then the exact same distance of
	<quantity><mag>50.5</mag><unit base="metre" prefix="kilo" /></quantity>
	would be traversed over such a trip.
	In <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-camrose-wetaskiwin" />,
	this equality of distances is represented by equality of the red and blue areas.
	</p>

	<aside><p> We take <q>average speed</q> to mean <q>average rate of accumulation of distance</q>. </p></aside>

	<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-camrose-wetaskiwin">
		<caption> Maintaining a constant speed at the average speed value traverses the same distance. </caption>
		<image width="80%">
			<description>Graph comparing accumulation as area between constant average rate and variable rate in a rate-of-travel model.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/camrose-wetaskiwin.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<p>
We won't always use <m>t = 0</m> as the start of the time interval,
nor will it always be the case that the initial quantity is assumed to be <m>0</m>,
so here is a formula that takes both those possibilities into account.
</p>

<identity xml:id="pattern-avg-rate">
	<title>Average rate of accumulation formula</title>
	<p>
	Given model <m>q(t)</m> representing the amount of some quantity,
	the average rate of accumulation over the time interval <m>t_0 \le t \le t_1</m> is
	<me> \avg{r} = \slope{q}{t} = \frac{ q(t_1) - q(t_0) }{ t_1 - t_0 } </me>.
	</p>
</identity>

<remark><p>
	The formula in <xref ref="pattern-avg-rate" /> is an example of what is called a <term>difference quotient</term>,
	as it is literally a <q>quotient of two differences.</q>
</p></remark>

<p>
We can interpret the formula in <xref ref="pattern-avg-rate" /> in words as
<me> \text{avg rate} = \frac{\text{accumulation}}{\text{duration}} </me>,
where <me> \text{accumulation} = (\text{final quantity}) - (\text{initial quantity}) </me>.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Calculating average rate of accumulation from quantity</title>
	<p>
	You check your investment account and find a balance of <m>\$10,385.92</m>.
	Four weeks later, you check again and find a balance of <m>\$10,593.64</m>.
	So over that time period, your account has accumulated
	<me> 10,593.64 - 10,385.92 = 207.72 </me>
	dollars,
	at an average rate of
	<me> \frac{207.72}{4} = 51.93 </me>
	dollars per week.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-avg-rate-from-quantity-model">
	<title>Calculating average rate of accumulation from a quantity model</title>

	<p>
	Consider an object launched upward with initial velocity
	<quantity>
		<mag>30</mag>
		<unit base="metre" />
		<per base="second" />
	</quantity>,
	from the surface of an airless planet where acceleration due to gravity is
	<quantity>
		<mag>10</mag>
		<unit base="metre" />
		<per base="second" exp="2" />
	</quantity>.
	According to the analysis <xref ref="example-poly-parabolic-motion" />,
	the objects height above the surface at any time <m>t \ge 0</m> can be determined using the model
	<me> h(t) = -5 t^2 + 30 t </me>,
	with <m>t</m> measured in seconds.
	(In <xref ref="example-poly-parabolic-motion" /> we used the traditional physics notation <m>s(t)</m> to represent the position function,
	but here we will use <m>h(t)</m> in its place to avoid confusion with the use of the letter s to represent seconds as the unit of time.)
	</p>

	<p>
	The <q>quantity</q> being measured here is <em>height above the surface</em>,
	and we consider motion to be an accumulation (or loss) of height.
	In this case, <q>average rate of accumulation</q> really means <q>average velocity</q>.
	</p>

	<p>
	Suppose we would like to calculate the average velocity over the time domain <m>1 \le t \le 3</m>.
	The endpoint heights are
	<md>
		<mrow>
			h(1) \amp = -5 \cdot 1^2 + 30 \cdot 1
			\amp
			h(3) \amp = -5 \cdot 3^2 + 30 \cdot 3
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			\amp = 25 \text{,}
			\amp
			\amp = 45 \text{.}
		</mrow>
	</md>
	Using <xref ref="pattern-avg-rate" />,
	we have
	<md>
		<mrow> \avg{v} \amp = \slope{h}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{ h(3) - h(1) }{ 3 - 1 } </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{ 45 - 25 }{ 3 - 1 } </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{ 20 }{ 2 } </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 10 </mrow>
	</md>
	metres per second.
	</p>

</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-avg-rate-graph">
<title>Graphical interpretations of average rate of accumulation</title>

<p>
We can interpret average rate of accumulation graphically in two ways <mdash />
on the rate graph, and on the quantity graph.
</p>

<p>
On the rate graph,
the interpretation is precisely just a graphical restatement of the definition
(<xref ref="definition-avg-rate" />),
as accumulation is equal to total (oriented) area under the rate graph
(<xref ref="principle-integ-definite-is-area" />).
</p>

<insight xml:id="principle-avg-rate-area-on-rate-graph">
	<title>Graphical interpretation of an average rate on the rate graph</title>
	<p> The average rate of accumulation is the constant rate value that will create the same (oriented) area amount over the same domain. </p>
</insight>

<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-area-on-rate-graph">
	<caption>
		Interpreting accumulation as the net oriented area under the rate graph over time domain <m> t_0 \le t \le t_1 </m>,
		the rectangle of height <m>\avg{r}</m> bounds an equivalent area over that domain,
		so that the rectangular green area is exactly equal to the total of the blue area and the (negative) red area.
	</caption>
	<image width="67%">
		<description>Interpreting an average rate graphically as bounding an equivalent area.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/bound-same-area.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p>
But on the quantity graph,
the formula
<me> \avg{r} = \slope{q}{t} = \frac{ q(t_1) - q(t_0) }{ t_1 - t_0 } </me>
leads to a completely interpretation.
The points <m>\bbrac{t_0, q(t_0)}</m> and <m>\bbrac{t_1, q(t_1)}</m> lie on the graph of the rate function,
the line segment connecting them is called a <term>secant line</term> for the graph,
and the formula for <m>\avg{r}</m> above is just the <em>rise-over-run</em> formula for the slope of that secant line.
</p>

<insight xml:id="principle-avg-rate-secant-slope-on-quantity-graph">
	<title>Graphical interpretation of an average rate on the quantity graph</title>
	<p> The average rate of accumulation is the slope of the secant line connecting the points on the quantity graph at the endpoints of the domain. </p>
</insight>

<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-slope-on-quantity-graph">
	<caption> Average rate of accumulation as a slope on the quantity graph. </caption>
	<image width="67%">
		<description>Interpreting an average rate graphically as a slope of a secant line.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/secant.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<example>
	<title>Average velocity</title>

	<p>
	Let's return to the situation of <xref ref="example-avg-rate-from-quantity-model" />.
	We have previously plotted both position and velocity graphs for this parabolic motion in <xref ref="figure-poly-parabolic-motion" />.
	According to <xref ref="principle-avg-rate-secant-slope-on-quantity-graph" />,
	the average velocity of
	<quantity>
		<mag>10</mag>
		<unit base="metre" />
		<per base="second" />
	</quantity>
	that we calculated represents the slope of a secant line on the position graph.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-secant-on-height-graph">
		<caption> An average velocity as a secant-line slope on the position graph. </caption>
		<image width="60%">
			<description>An average velocity as a secant-line slope on the position graph.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/parabolic-motion-secant.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	At the same time,
	if we use the calculated <m>\avg{v}</m> as a constant velocity over the same time domain,
	we achieve the same accumulation of height.
	According to <xref ref="principle-avg-rate-area-on-rate-graph" />,
	this means that the green and red areas in <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-area-on-velocity-graph" /> are the same.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-area-on-velocity-graph">
		<caption> An average velocity as an <q>equivalent</q> constant velocity on the velocity graph. </caption>
		<image width="60%">
			<description>An average velocity as an <q>equivalent</q> constant velocity on the velocity graph.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/parabolic-motion-area.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<example xml:id="example-avg-rate-linear-quantity">
	<title>Average rate for a linear quantity model</title>

	<p>
	Suppose we have a linear quantity model
	<me> q(t) = m t + q_0 </me>,
	where <m>q_0 = q(0)</m> is the initial quantity.
	Over any time domain <m>t_0 \le t \le t_1</m>,
	the average rate of accumulation is
	<md>
		<mrow> \avg{r} \amp = \slope{q}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{ q(t_1) - q(t_0) }{ t_1 - t_0 } </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{ (m t_1 + q_0) - (m t_0 + q_0) }{ t_1 - t_0 } </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{ m (t_1 - t_0) }{ t_1 - t_0 } </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = m </mrow>
	</md>.
	The average rate of accumulation is the same, no matter what time domain is used,
	and is equal to the slope of the quantity's graph,
	so that our model could be expressed as
	<me> q(t) = \avg{r} t + q_0 </me>.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-secant-on-linear">
		<caption> A secant on a linear quantity graph is parallel to the graph. </caption>
		<image width="60%">
			<description> A graph depicting the fact that a secant on a linear quantity graph is parallel to the graph. </description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/linear-quantity.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	According to <xref ref="pattern-poly-constant-rate" />,
	a linear quantity model arises from a constant rate model.
	So it is not surprising that the average rate of change is always the same value for a linear quantity model <mdash />
	the average of a constant is that constant.
	</p>

</example>

</section>

<section>
<title>Approximating instantaneous rate of accumulation</title>

<p>
Observing that your rain gauge has collected
<quantity><mag>4</mag><unit base="metre" prefix="milli" /></quantity>
of water over
<quantity><mag>10</mag><unit base="hour" /></quantity>
says nothing about how intense the rainfall was at any given moment during that time.
We'll need more data to be more specific.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-avg-rate-multi-day-car-trip">
	<title>A multi-day road trip</title>

	<p>
	You drive from Edmonton to Toronto,
	a total distance of approximately
	<quantity><mag>3375</mag><unit base="metre" prefix="kilo" /></quantity>.
	The trip takes a total of
	<quantity><mag>35</mag><unit base="hour" /></quantity>
	of driving time split over three days,
	for a total-trip average speed of approximately
	<me> \frac{3375}{35} = 96.4 </me>
	kilometres per hour.
	</p>

	<p>
	However, on the first day you are driving on straight, flat, Prairie highways with higher speed limits,
	and cover
	<quantity><mag>1305</mag><unit base="metre" prefix="kilo" /></quantity>
	over
	<quantity><mag>13</mag><unit base="hour" /></quantity>
	of driving,
	for a first-day average speed of approximately
	<me> \frac{1305}{13} = 100.4 </me>
	kilometres per hour.
	</p>

	<p>
	The second day is much more of a slog through never-ending Northwestern Ontario on two-lane highways with lower speed limits,
	through hilly terrain with lots of transport trucks and camper-trailers but few opportunities to pass.
	You cover
	<quantity><mag>1385</mag><unit base="metre" prefix="kilo" /></quantity>,
	but it takes you
	<quantity><mag>15</mag><unit base="hour" /></quantity>
	of driving,
	for a second-day average speed of approximately
	<me> \frac{1385}{15} = 92.3 </me>
	kilometres per hour.
	</p>

	<p>
	The final stretch is better <mdash />
	still a lot of hilly terrain until you get into Southern Ontario,
	but many more stretches of divided highway with two lanes in each direction and higher speed limits.
	The last
	<quantity><mag>685</mag><unit base="metre" prefix="kilo" /></quantity>
	takes you
	<quantity><mag>7</mag><unit base="hour" /></quantity>,
	for a final-day average speed of approximately
	<me> \frac{685}{7} = 97.9 </me>
	kilometres per hour.
	</p>

</example>

<p>
<xref ref="example-avg-rate-multi-day-car-trip" />
demonstrates that we can be more precise about rate behaviour by <q>zooming in</q> from <q>global</q> data to more <q>local</q> data.
In <xref ref="example-avg-rate-multi-day-car-trip" />,
this <q>zooming in</q> is from whole-trip to day-by-day.
We start to see patterns of variation in the rate of accumulation if we consider shorter time durations.
What if we take this idea further?
</p>

<example xml:id="example-avg-rate-speedometer">
	<title>Designing a basic speedometer</title>

	<p>
	One of your hobbies is building remote-controlled (RC) vehicles.
	You would like your current model to wirelessly relay data to a communication app on your phone that will let you monitor its speed as close to real-time as possible.
	A <term>tachometer</term> is a device that counts revolutions of a rotating object.
	You install one on the rear axle of your RC vehicle,
	and interface it to the Bluetooth module on the control board.
	Your phone app now receives axle revolution counts every
	<quantity><mag>100</mag><unit base="second" prefix="milli" /></quantity>.
	(Assume that the tachometer is reasonably high-precision,
	so that fractional revolutions are reported.)
	How can you use this data to get an idea of the vehicle's speed?
	</p>

	<p>
	Let <m>q(t)</m> represent the quantity of axle revolutions reported at time <m>t</m>,
	where <m>t</m> is measured in milliseconds.
	Then <me> \change{q} = q(t) - q(t - 100) </me>
	represents the number of revolutions in a given
	<quantity><mag>100</mag><unit base="second" prefix="milli" /></quantity> interval,
	The rear wheels on the RC vehicle measure <quantity><mag>108</mag><unit base="metre" prefix="milli" /></quantity> in diameter,
	so that the distance travelled in a <quantity><mag>100</mag><unit base="second" prefix="milli" /></quantity> interval is
	<me> \change{s} = 108 \pi \change{q} </me>.
	So you program the app on your phone to display the result of calculating
	<me> \slope{s}{t} = \frac{ 108 \pi \bbrac{ q(t) - q(t - 100) } }{100} \cdot \frac{3600}{1000} </me>,
	where
	<ul>
		<li> <m>q(t)</m> represents the most recent tachometer reading </li>
		<li> <m>q(t - 100)</m> represents the previous tachometer reading </li>
		<li> the extra factor of <m>3600 / 1000</m> is to convert from millimetres per millisecond to kilometres per hour. </li>
	</ul>
	</p>

</example>

<p>
Both <xref ref="example-avg-rate-multi-day-car-trip" />
and <xref ref="example-avg-rate-speedometer" />
demonstrate the same pattern <mdash />
we can break the time domain up into smaller subdomains of length <m>\change{t}</m> to get more precise information.
On a short enough time domain,
as in <xref ref="example-avg-rate-speedometer" />,
our average rate calculations give us a pretty good idea of the actual rate.
</p>

<insight xml:id="principle-avg-rage-approximates-instant-rate">
	<title>Average rate of accumulation over short domains approximates actual rate of accumulation</title>
	<p>
	In general,
	given a quantity function <m>q(t)</m> over a time domain <m>t_0 \le t \le t_1</m> so that
	<me> \change{t} = t_1 - t_0 </me>
	is sufficiently small,
	it is reasonable to approximate
	<me> r(t) \approx \avg{r} </me>
	for all <m>t</m> in that time domain.
	</p>
</insight>

<remark><p>
	The meaning of <q>sufficiently small</q> is relative to the particular quantity function <m>q(t)</m>,
	the time domain considered,
	and what one is willing to accept as <q>reasonable</q> in the approximation.
</p></remark>

<p>
The reason that we need <m>\change{t}</m> to be small for the approximation to be <q>reasonable</q> is that if <m>\change{t}</m> is too long,
we will capture information that is irrelevant to the current rate of accumulation.
Here is an extreme example to illustrate this.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-avg-rate-bailing-tub">
	<title>Bailing a tub by the bucket-full</title>

	<p>
	You are slowly bailing out a
	<quantity><mag>50</mag><unit base="liter" /></quantity>
	tub using a
	<quantity><mag>10</mag><unit base="liter" /></quantity>
	pail.
	You are able to fill and empty a pail-full every
	<quantity><mag>5</mag><unit base="second" /></quantity>.
	(Let's assume you are able to get a full pail even when there is only
	<quantity><mag>10</mag><unit base="liter" /></quantity>
	left in the tub.)
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-bailing-graph">
		<caption> Quantity of water in tub during emptying. </caption>
		<image width="60%">
			<description> A graph of volume versus time for the process of bailing water out of a tub. </description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/tub-step.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	If we compute <m>\avg{r}</m> over the full time domain <m> 0 \le t \le 25</m>,
	we obtain
	<md>
		<mrow> \avg{r} \amp = \slope{q}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{ q(25) - q(0) }{ 25 - 0 } </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{ 0 - 50 }{ 25 } </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = -2 </mrow>
	</md>
	in litres per second,
	where we have obtained a negative result because the tub was losing water rather than accumulating water.
	This value represents the slope of the red line segment in
	<xref ref="figure-avg-rate-bailing-slopes" />.
	</p>

	<p>
	But clearly the rate of accumulation (or, really, the rate of <em>loss</em>) of water in the tub is
	<quantity><mag>0</mag><unit base="liter" /><per base="second" /></quantity>
	at any instant between scoops with the pail.
	That is, we expect <m>r(t) = 0</m> for every value of <m>t</m> outside of the times that the pail is being filled from the tub.
	We can better approximate these instantaneous rate of accumulation values with an average rate of accumulation calculation over a shorter time domain,
	so that we focus only on <q>local</q> data rather than using the entire <q>global</q> collection of data.
	For example, over the time domain <m>6 \le t \le 9</m>,
	we have
	<md>
		<mrow> \avg{r} \amp = \slope{q}{t} </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{ q(9) - q(6) }{ 9 - 6 } </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{ 30 - 30 }{ 3 } </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 0 </mrow>
	</md>.
	This value represents the slope of the green line segment in
	<xref ref="figure-avg-rate-bailing-slopes" />.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-bailing-slopes">
		<caption> Two secant lines on the quantity graph. </caption>
		<image width="60%">
			<description>
				A graph of volume versus time for the process of bailing water out of a tub,
				including two secant lines.
			</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/tub-slopes.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

<insight xml:id="principle-avg-rage-shorter-duration">
	<title>Shorter time domain yields better approximation</title>
	<p>
	In general,
	given a quantity function <m>q(t)</m>,
	an average rate calculation over a shorter time domain will yield a better approximation of the actual rate of change,
	compared to an average rate calculation over a longer time domain.
	</p>
</insight>

<remark><p><ul>
	<li>
		Compare <xref ref="principle-avg-rage-shorter-duration" />
		with <xref ref="principle-integ-riemann-more-steps" /> <mdash />
		both involve obtaining a better approximation by using smaller values of <m>\change{t}</m>.
	</li>
	<li>
		It is possible to come up with <q>wild</q> examples where <xref ref="principle-avg-rage-shorter-duration" /> does not hold,
		which is why we have the proviso <q>In general.</q>
	</li>
</ul></p></remark>

</section>

<section>
<title>Calculating instantaneous rate of accumulation</title>

<p>
Suppose we have a quantity model <m>q(t)</m> and we want to calculate a specific rate value <m>r(t^\ast)</m> exactly.
Just as we computed exact accumulation values from approximations of (hopefully) increasing accuracy,
we take the same approach here.
But to see a pattern of increasing accuracy in a collection of approximations,
we need a more systematic approach than just <q>compute <m>\avg{r}</m> over a short time domain containing <m>t^\ast</m>.</q>
Here are three such approaches.
</p>

<aside><title>Notation</title><p>
	Here <m>t^\ast</m> does not indicate a <q>sample point</q> in a Riemann sum <mdash />
	instead the asterisk just marks this <m>t</m> value as of <q>special</q> interest.
</p></aside>

<definition xml:id="definition-avg-rate-three-standard-approximations">
	<title>Three standard difference approximations to rate</title>

	<p>
	Assume a small value of <m>\change{t}</m> has been chosen

	<ul>

		<li>
			<title>Forward difference approximation at <m>t^\ast</m></title>
			<p>
			The average-rate approximation to <m>r(t^\ast)</m> over the time domain <me> t^\ast \le t \le t^\ast + \change{t} </me>,
			so that <me> r(t^\ast) \approx \frac{ q(t^\ast + \change{t}) - q(t^\ast) }{ \change{t} } </me>.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<title>Backward difference approximation at <m>t^\ast</m></title>
			<p>
			The average-rate approximation to <m>r(t^\ast)</m> over the time domain <me> t^\ast - \change{t} \le t \le t^\ast </me>,
			so that <me> r(t^\ast) \approx \frac{ q(t^\ast) - q(t^\ast - \change{t}) }{ \change{t} } </me>.
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<title>Central difference approximation at <m>t^\ast</m></title>
			<p>
			The average-rate approximation to <m>r(t^\ast)</m> over the time domain <me> t^\ast - c \le t \le t^\ast + c </me> for
			<me> c = {\change{t} \over 2} </me>,
			so that <me> r(t^\ast) \approx \frac{ q(t^\ast + c) - q(t^\ast - c) }{ \change{t} } </me>.
			</p>
		</li>

	</ul>

	</p>

</definition>

<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-forward-backward-central">
	<caption>
		Secant lines whose slopes represent the forward (green), backward (red), and central (blue) approximations to rate.
	</caption>
	<image width="67%">
		<description>Secant lines on a graph whose slopes represent the forward, backward, and central approximations to rate.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/forward-backward-central.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<remark><p><ul>

	<li>
		Since <me> \frac{ q(t^\ast) - q(t^\ast - \change{t}) }{ \change{t} } = \frac{ q(t^\ast - \change{t}) - q(t^\ast) }{ - \change{t} } </me>,
		the forward and backward approximations can be unified into one by using the formula for the forward difference approximation but allowing <m>\change{t}</m> to be chosen as either a positive or negative value.
	</li>

	<li>
		The central difference formula could also be written as
		<me> \frac{ q(t^\ast + c) - q(t^\ast - c) }{ 2 c } </me>.
	</li>

</ul></p></remark>

<p>
Just as we took the number of rectangles <m>n</m> to be larger and larger in upper and lower sum approximations to accumulation and looked for a pattern,
here we want to take <m>\change{t}</m> to be smaller and smaller and look for a pattern in the above approximations.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-avg-rate-cubic-instant-rate">
	<title>Instantaneous rate for a cubic quantity model</title>

	<p>
	Suppose we have quantity model <m>q(t) = t^3</m>.
	Let's use Sage to calculate average-rate approximations to the actual rate <m>r(t^\ast)</m> for <m>t^\ast = 2</m>.
	Since Sage doesn't like Greek letters very much,
	we'll write <c>dt</c> in place of <m>\change{t}</m>.
	We'll also write <c>u</c> in place of <m>t^\ast</m>.
	</p>

	<sage>

		<input>
			var('t,u')
			q(t) = t^3
			u = 2
			dt = 0.5
			forward = ( q(u + dt) - q(u) ) / dt
			backward = ( q(u) - q(u - dt) ) / dt
			central = ( q(u + dt / 2) - q(u - dt / 2) ) / dt
			print("forward  =", forward)
			print("backward =", backward)
			print("central  =", central)
		</input>

		<output>
			forward  = 15.2500000000000
			backward = 9.25000000000000
			central  = 12.0625000000000
		</output>

	</sage>

	<p>
	After evaluating the Sage cell above,
	change the value of <c>dt</c> to something smaller and re-evaluate.
	Repeat with smaller and smaller values of <c>dt</c> until the forward, backward, and central difference approximations all seem to be <q>converging</q> to a single value.
	</p>

</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-avg-rate-derivative">
<title>The derivative</title>

<p>
In many cases we can use average-rate approximations with smaller and smaller <m>\change{t}</m> and observe an obvious pattern toward some specific value.
When approximating accumulation with Riemann sums,
we obtained the definite integral value by observing the upper and lower sums <q>squeezing</q> together toward a specific value.
Unfortunately, there is no systematic way an <q>upper average rate</q> or <q>lower average rate</q> to squeeze together,
so we will have to be a little more subtle.
</p>

<definition xml:id="definition-avg-rate-derivative-value">
	<title>Derivative value</title>

	<p>
	Given a function <m>q(t)</m> on domain <m>a \le t \le b</m>
	and a specific time <m>t^\ast</m> strictly within that domain
	(so that <m>a \lt t^\ast \lt b</m>),
	suppose there exists one unique number <m>d</m> so that values of average rate calculations
	<me> \slope{q}{t} </me>
	over subdomains containing <m>t^\ast</m> can be made arbitrarily close to <m>d</m> by taking <m>\change{t}</m> sufficiently small.
	</p>

	<p>
	In this case, we say that <m>q(t)</m> is <term>differentiable</term> at <m>t = t^\ast</m>,
	call the value <m>d</m> the <term>derivative of <m>q(t)</m> at <m>t = t^\ast</m></term>,
	and write <me> \funceval{\ddt{q}}{t = t^\ast} </me> to represent the value of <m>d</m>.
	</p>

</definition>

<remark><title>Derivative versus rate</title><p>
	Given that we use average rate calculations over short time domains to approximate actual rate,
	we expect that <me> \funceval{\ddt{q}}{t = t^\ast} = r(t^\ast) </me> will be true,
	and in fact we will be able to theoretically justify this in later chapters.
</p></remark>

<p>
Compare the notation
<me> \slope{q}{t} \to \ddt{q} </me>
with the previous notation
<me> \sum_{k = 1}^{n} r(t_k^\ast) \change{t_k} \to \ccmint{a}{b}{r(t)}{t} </me>.
In both situations, we are computing approximations that (we hope) are more and more accurate,
until they are so close we can't tell the difference.
And in both notational choices,
<m>\change{t}</m> becomes <m>dt</m>,
signally to the reader that we have let our approximations become <q>infinitely close</q> to the <q>actual</q> value by considering time subdomain(s) of <q>infinitesimal</q> length.
</p>

<p>
Now, what does <q>arbitrarily close</q> and <q>sufficiently small</q> mean?
Arbitrarily close means that we may choose any error bounds around the proposed value <m>d</m> that we like,
and in response we will be able to set a <q>maximum</q> <m>\change{t}</m> so that the result of <em>every</em> average rate calculation over a time subdomain containing <m>t^\ast</m> and of that maximum <m>\change{t}</m> length or smaller will fall within our error bounds around <m>d</m>.
That is, given an arbitrary error bound <m>\epsilon \gt 0</m>,
we expect to always find that
<me> \slope{q}{t} = d \pm \epsilon </me>,
as long as the average rate is calculated over a domain containing <m>t^\ast</m> and with <m>\change{t}</m> smaller than some particular maximum.
(Changing the error bound value <m>\epsilon</m> will likely require a different maximum <m>\change{t}</m> value <mdash />
in general, we expect tighter error bounds around <m>d</m> to require a smaller maximum <m>\change{t}</m> value.)
</p>

<remark><p>
	It was not necessary to have this sort of <q>error bound</q> reasoning in the definition of the <xref ref="definition-integ-definite" text="title" />,
	as the upper and lower sums effectively acted as the error bounds.
</p></remark>

<example xml:id="example-avg-rate-within-error-bound">
	<title>Determining rate within a given constraint</title>

	<p>
	Let's revisit <xref ref="example-avg-rate-cubic-instant-rate" />.
	Hopefully you found that the three average-rate approximations to <m>r(2)</m> all became close to <m>12</m> as <m>\change{t}</m>
	(<c>dt</c> in the Sage code)
	was made smaller.
	</p>

	<p>
	Below is some Sage code to test an arbitrarily chosen error bound around <m>12</m>.
	(We use <c>e</c> in place of the Greek letter <m>\epsilon</m>.)
	Try to determine a small enough <m>\change{t}</m> value
	(again, represented as <c>dt</c> in the Sage code) so that all three of the forward, backward, and central approximations
	are no more than the value of <c>e</c> away from <m>12</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	Once you've done this,
	try changing <c>e</c> to a smaller value,
	and see if the previous value of <c>dt</c> still works,
	or whether you need to make it smaller.
	</p>

	<sage>

		<input>
			var('t,u')
			q(t) = t^3
			u = 2
			dt = 0.5
			e = 0.1
			forward = ( q(u + dt) - q(u) ) / dt
			backward = ( q(u) - q(u - dt) ) / dt
			central = ( q(u + dt / 2) - q(u - dt / 2) ) / dt
			print("forward =", forward)
			print("Is forward approximation between", 12 - e, "and", 12 + e, "?")
			print()
			print("backward =", backward)
			print("Is backward approximation between", 12 - e, "and", 12 + e, "?")
			print()
			print("central =", central)
			print("Is central approximation between", 12 - e, "and", 12 + e, "?")
		</input>

		<output>
			forward = 15.2500000000000
			Difference between 12 and forward = -3.25000000000000

			backward = 9.25000000000000
			Difference between 12 and backward = 2.75000000000000

			central = 12.0625000000000
			Difference between 12 and central = -0.0625000000000000
		</output>

	</sage>

</example>

</section>

<section>
<title>Graphical interpretation of the derivative</title>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-avg-rate-tangents">
<title>Tangent lines</title>

<p>
Consider what happens on the quantity graph when we form the forward, backward, and central approximations to the quantity's rate of accumulation at a specific time <m>t = t^\ast</m> for several iterations of smaller <m>\change{t}</m> values.
For emphasis, we will extend the associated secant line segments to actual lines.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-converging-to-tangent">
	<caption>
		Three iterations of secant lines whose slopes represent the forward (green), backward (red), and central (blue) approximations to rate,
		using decreasing values of <m>\change{t}</m>.
	</caption>

	<sbsgroup width="67%">

		<sidebyside><figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-converging-to-tangent-1">
			<caption>Somewhat large <m>\change{t}</m>.</caption>
			<image>
				<description>
					Secant lines on a graph whose slopes represent the forward, backward, and central approximations to rate,
					using a somewhat long time subdomain.
				</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/forward-backward-central-to-tangent-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure></sidebyside>

		<sidebyside><figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-converging-to-tangent-2">
			<caption>Smaller <m>\change{t}</m>.</caption>
			<image>
				<description>
					Secant lines on a graph whose slopes represent the forward, backward, and central approximations to rate,
					using a shorter time subdomain.
				</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/forward-backward-central-to-tangent-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure></sidebyside>

		<sidebyside><figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-converging-to-tangent-3">
			<caption>Small <m>\change{t}</m>.</caption>
			<image>
				<description>
					Secant lines on a graph whose slopes represent the forward, backward, and central approximations to rate,
					using a very short time subdomain.
				</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/forward-backward-central-to-tangent-3.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure></sidebyside>

	</sbsgroup>

</figure>

<p>
When <m>q(t)</m> is differentiable at <m>t = t^\ast</m>,
by definition the slopes of the three lines in each of the subfigures of <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-converging-to-tangent" />
must become arbitrarily close to some specific value as <m>\change{t}</m> is made smaller,
hence arbitrarily close to each other.
As you can see in the sequence in <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-converging-to-tangent" />,
not only do these three lines become closer to being parallel as <m>\change{t}</m> becomes smaller,
it is appears that if we continued to make <m>\change{t}</m> smaller they would <q>converge</q> to becoming the <em>exact same line</em>.
We could think of this one line that the three are converging toward as the case of <m>\change{t}</m> becoming <m>dt</m> <mdash />
a secant line over a subdomain containing <m>t^\ast</m> of length so small that the endpoints of the subdomain are essentially at <m>t^\ast</m> as well.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-tangent-line">
	<caption>A <q>secant</q> line over a subdomain of <q>infinitesimal length</q> <m>dt</m>.</caption>
	<image width="67%">
		<description> A <q>secant</q> line on a graph over an infinitesimally short time subdomain. </description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/tangent.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<p> The line in <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-tangent-line" /> has a special name. </p>

<definition xml:id="definition-avg-rage-tangent-line">
	<title>Tangent line</title>
	<p>
	If <m>q(t)</m> is differentiable at <m>t = t^\ast</m>,
	then the line that passes through the point <m>\bbrac{ t^\ast, q(t^\ast) }</m> with slope
	<me> \funceval{\ddt{q}}{t = t^\ast} </me>
	is called the <term>tangent line</term> to the graph of <m>q(t)</m> at <m>t = t^\ast</m>.
	</p>
</definition>

<identity xml:id="pattern-avg-rate-tangent-line-equation">
	<title>Equation of a tangent line</title>
	<p>
	If <m>q(t)</m> is differentiable at <m>t = t^\ast</m>,
	then the equation of the tangent line to the graph of <m>q(t)</m> at <m>t = t^\ast</m> is
	<me> y = m t + b </me>
	where
	<md>
		<mrow>
			m \amp = \funceval{\ddt{q}}{t = t^\ast}
			\text{,}
			b \amp = q(t^\ast) - m t^\ast
			\text{.}
		</mrow>
	</md>
	</p>
</identity>

<example>
	<title>Determining a tangent line equation</title>

	<p>
	Once again, let's revisit the quantity function <m>q(t) = t^3</m> previously analysed
	in <xref ref="example-avg-rate-cubic-instant-rate" />
	and <xref ref="example-avg-rate-within-error-bound" />,
	where we found that
	<me> \funceval{\ddt{q}}{t = 2} = 12 </me>.
	So the tangent line through the point <m>(2, 8)</m> with slope <m>m = 12</m> is
	<md>
		<mrow> y \amp = 12 t + (8 - 12 \cdot 2) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 12 t - 16 </mrow>
	</md>
	</p>

	<figure>
		<caption> A tangent line to the graph of <m>q(t) = t^3</m>. </caption>
		<image width="67%">
			<description> A tangent line on the cubic graph. </description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/example-tangent.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

</example>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Local linearity</title>

<p>
Another way to think of both the derivative value and the tangent line is through the concept of <term>local linearization</term>.
Graphically, shrinking <m>\change{t}</m> is similar to <q>zooming in</q> on the point <m>\bbrac{ t^\ast, q(t^\ast) }</m> on the graph of <m>q(t)</m>.
In <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-local-linearity" />,
a blue box of width <m>\change{t}</m> is drawn around the point <m>\bbrac{ t^\ast, q(t^\ast) }</m>,
and then that square is used as the frame for the next zoom level with a smaller <m>\change{t}</m>.
</p>

<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-local-linearity">
	<caption> Zooming in to see the <term>local linearity</term> of a graph. </caption>

	<sbsgroup>

		<sidebyside widths="67%"><figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-local-linearity-1">
			<image>
				<description> Graph with a box that will be zoomed into next. </description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/local-linearity-1.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure></sidebyside>

		<sidebyside widths="45% 45%">

			<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-local-linearity-2">
				<image>
					<description> Graph with a box that will be zoomed into next. </description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/local-linearity-2.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

			<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-local-linearity-3">
				<image>
					<description> Graph with a box that will be zoomed into next. </description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/local-linearity-3.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

		</sidebyside>

		<sidebyside widths="45% 45%">

			<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-local-linearity-4">
				<image>
					<description> Graph with a box that will be zoomed into next. </description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/local-linearity-4.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

			<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-local-linearity-5">
				<image>
					<description> Graph with a box that will be zoomed into next. </description>
					<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/local-linearity-5.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
				</image>
			</figure>

		</sidebyside>

	</sbsgroup>

</figure>

<p>
As you can see in <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-local-linearity" />,
zooming in around a point excludes more and more of the variation in the graph,
until the graph becomes essentially linear through the point being considered.
Not every point on every graph will exhibit this kind of pattern when zooming in,
but it will always be present at differentiable points,
with the derivative value describing the slope of that essentially linear piece of the graph.
</p>

</subsection>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-avg-rage-non-diff">
<title>Some non-differentiable examples</title>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-avg-rage-non-diff-cusps">
<title>Cusps</title>

<example>
	<title>Measuring distance rather than displacement</title>

	<p>
	A sensor is placed to measure the <em>distance</em> of some object from the sensor.
	For a period of time, the object moves directly toward the sensor at a constant rate,
	then passes by it and continues on the same path at the same rate away from the sensor.
	A typical plot of the data capture by the sensor appears in <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-sensor-distance" />.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-sensor-distance">
		<caption>
			Graph of distance from a sensor of an object in motion (blue),
			with backward (red), forward (green), and central (purple) secant lines.
		</caption>
		<image width="67%">
			<description>
				A graph of an object's distance from a sensor as the object travels toward and then away from the sensor, with accompanying secant lines.
			</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/tangent.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	The distance graph is a V-shape,
	as in <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-sensor-distance" />,
	where <m>t = t^\ast</m> is the instant that the object passes the sensor.
	We can see that no matter how far we zoom in around <m>t = t^\ast</m>,
	the graph will always have a V-shape there,
	and will never by locally linear around <m>t = t^\ast</m>.
	So we expect the function to not be differentiable at <m>t = t^\ast</m>.
	Indeed,
	if we compute forward, backward, and central average-rate approximations to the rate at <m>t = t^\ast</m>,
	we will always find that the forward average rate is <m>r</m> (the slope of the right <q>arm</q> of the V-shape),
	the backward average rate is <m>- r</m> (the slope of the left <q>arm</q> of the V-shape),
	and the central average rate is <m>0</m>,
	where <m>r</m> is the constant rate of travel of the object.
	So if we choose an error bound of <m>\epsilon = r/2</m>, say,
	it will be impossible to shrink <m>\change{t}</m> so that all three approximations are within the error bound of some proposed rate value,
	no matter what proposed rate value is tried.
	</p>

</example>

<p>
The sharp corner at <m>t = t^\ast</m> in <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-sensor-distance" /> is called a <term>cusp</term>,
and functions with such a feature are never differentiable at that point.
</p>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-avg-rage-non-diff-jump">
<title>Jump discontinuities</title>

<!-- TODO reference jump discontinuity from preliminary chapters ? -->

<example>
	<title>Differentiability of step functions</title>

	<p>
	Returning to <xref ref="example-avg-rate-bailing-tub" />,
	it would be non-trivial to devise a model for the changing water level during the short periods of time where a full pail is being lifted out of the tub.
	The model graphed in <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-bailing-graph" /> is a crude attempt to make the graph appear to be realistic,
	but often when modelling it is more expedient to <em>not</em> attempt to realistically model every aspect of the system,
	using a simplified model instead.
	In this case,
	it is very easy to create a simple model for the amount of water in the tank by using a step function.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-simplified-bailing-graph">
		<caption> Quantity of water in tub during emptying as a step function. </caption>
		<image width="60%">
			<description> A graph of a step function as volume versus time modelling the process of bailing water out of a tub. </description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/tub-stepped.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	Consider the point on the graph at <m>t = 5</m>.
	If we <q>zoomed in</q> around this point,
	we would see only a line <em>segment</em> on the right,
	but nothing on the left.
	Since we do not see a linear graph through the point being considered,
	we would not call this graph locally linear at <m>t = 5</m>,
	and so we should expect <m>q(t)</m> to not be differentiable at <m>t = 5</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	Also consider what would happen if we calculated some average rates around <m>t = 5</m> for small <m>\change{t}</m>.
	Backward and central average rates would be large negative values,
	since the corresponding secant lines would have left endpoints on the upper step at output level <m>40</m> and right endpoints on the lower step at output level <m>30</m>.
	But forward average rates would always be <m>0</m>,
	since the corresponding secant lines would have both endpoints on the lower step.
	There is no possibility that these average rates could all be made close enough to each other to fit in an arbitrarily small error bound around some proposed rate value,
	so the function is not differentiable at <m>t = 5</m>.
	</p>

	<p> And the same would be true at all times where the step function <q>steps</q>. </p>

</example>

</subsection>


<subsection xml:id="subsection-avg-rage-non-diff-singular">
<title>Singularities</title>

<example>

	<p>
	Consider a model function <me> q(t) = \frac{1}{(t-2)^2} </me>.
	This function has a singularity at <m>t = 2</m>,
	where <m>q(t) \to \infty</m> for both <m>t \to 2^\plus</m> and <m>t \to 2^\minus</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
	Consider some average rate calculations around <m>t = 2</m>.
	Note that the definition of
	<xref ref="definition-avg-rate-derivative-value" text="title" />
	does specifically reference
	the <xref ref="definition-avg-rate-three-standard-approximations" text="title" />
	<mdash />
	for a given maximum <m>\change{t}</m>,
	we should consider <em>all</em> average-rate approximations of rate that involve that <m>\change{t}</m> or smaller.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-secant-on-singularity">
		<caption> Average rates near a singularity as secant-line slopes. </caption>
		<image width="60%">
			<description>Average rates near a singularity as secant-line slopes on the quantity graph.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/singularity-secants.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	From <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-secant-on-singularity" />,
	hopefully it is obvious that no matter how tightly around <m>t = 2</m> we restrict ourselves,
	we can always create average rate calculations with results that are arbitrarily large and positive
	(for example, by sliding the right endpoint of the green secant line upwards),
	others that are arbitrarily large and negative
	(for example, by sliding the left endpoint of the red secant line upwards),
	and others that are exactly <m>0</m>
	(for example, the purple secant line, or any similar horizontal secant line above it).
	Even worse,
	it is not possible to calculate forward or backward average-rate approximations,
	since <m>q(2)</m> is undefined.
	</p>

	<p> For these reasons, this function is not differentiable at the singularity at <m>t = 2</m>. </p>

</example>

</subsection>


<subsection xml:id="subsection-avg-rage-non-diff-vertical">
<title>Vertical tangents</title>

<example>
	<title>Vertical tangent</title>

	<p>
	Now consider a shifted cube-root function,
	<me> q(t) = 1 + \sqrt[3]{t - 1} </me>,
	and picture a secant line about <m>t = 1</m>.
	</p>

	<figure xml:id="figure-avg-rate-secant-on-vertical-tangent">
		<caption> Average rate as a secant-line slope near an instantaneously vertical point. </caption>
		<image width="60%">
			<description>Average rate as a secant-line slope near an instantaneously vertical point.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="avg-rate.d/vertical-secant.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>

	<p>
	As the red endpoints of the secant line in <xref ref="figure-avg-rate-secant-on-vertical-tangent" /> are drawn closer to <m>t = 1</m> to shrink <m>\change{t}</m> in the average rate calculation,
	the line segment will become more steep and its slope
	(representing the average rate)
	will become larger without bound.
	We could imagine that the result of the <em>secant-lines-become-tangent-line</em> process from <xref ref="subsection-avg-rate-tangents" /> is a vertical line at <m>t = 1</m> running through the graph at the point <m>(1,1)</m>,
	but we can't say that the function is differentiable at <m>t = 1</m> because a vertical line has undefined slope,
	and the <em>increasing-without-bound</em> average rate values do not display a pattern that converge to a specific number.
	</p>

</example>

</subsection>

</section>


